00:52:50.355 --> 00:52:52.730
AUDIENCE: Could you talk a
little bit about your decision

00:52:52.730 --> 00:52:54.885
tree if somebody
breaks into your house

00:52:54.885 --> 00:52:56.010
in the middle of the night?

00:52:56.010 --> 00:52:57.280
GERSHON BEN KEREN: Yeah, sure.

00:52:57.280 --> 00:52:57.780
OK.

00:52:57.780 --> 00:53:00.040
There's different
types of criminals.

00:53:00.040 --> 00:53:06.040
And individuals choose a
crime for a set of reasons.

00:53:06.040 --> 00:53:09.815
A good example is to
compare a burglar, somebody

00:53:09.815 --> 00:53:12.440
who breaks in, to a mugger.

00:53:12.440 --> 00:53:16.650
Burglary by and large nets
the person more money.

00:53:16.650 --> 00:53:19.510
So it's more profitable
to be a burglar

00:53:19.510 --> 00:53:21.780
than it is to be a mugger.

00:53:21.780 --> 00:53:23.970
The problem is, if
you're a burglar,

00:53:23.970 --> 00:53:27.030
you need to be tapped into
a criminal network who

00:53:27.030 --> 00:53:30.140
can change the goods
stolen into cash.

00:53:30.140 --> 00:53:33.170
So you need to know a fence.

00:53:33.170 --> 00:53:36.400
The other thing is,
that's going to take time.

00:53:36.400 --> 00:53:40.702
So you've got to have some
delayed gratification.

00:53:40.702 --> 00:53:41.910
The mugger doesn't have that.

00:53:41.910 --> 00:53:45.000
He wants that $20 so
he can go to his dealer

00:53:45.000 --> 00:53:47.094
and get the next fix.

00:53:47.094 --> 00:53:49.010
So you start to understand
when you understand

00:53:49.010 --> 00:53:51.790
what motivates people
towards crime a little bit

00:53:51.790 --> 00:53:55.190
about their different
characteristics.

00:53:55.190 --> 00:53:59.890
A burglar by and large is
going to burgle your house

00:53:59.890 --> 00:54:02.130
during the day whilst
you're at work.

00:54:02.130 --> 00:54:03.740
That's by and large.

00:54:03.740 --> 00:54:06.990
If you're looking at
things to deter burglars,

00:54:06.990 --> 00:54:09.430
occupancy is one,
giving the impression

00:54:09.430 --> 00:54:11.100
that you're actually home.

00:54:11.100 --> 00:54:14.070
Because burglars,
unlike muggers,

00:54:14.070 --> 00:54:16.429
don't really want to
interact with you.

00:54:16.429 --> 00:54:17.970
They want to go
about their business,

00:54:17.970 --> 00:54:20.770
because it takes time
to find everything,

00:54:20.770 --> 00:54:24.060
basically unhindered by the
potential presence of somebody

00:54:24.060 --> 00:54:25.170
there.

00:54:25.170 --> 00:54:27.650
The other one is a dog.

00:54:27.650 --> 00:54:32.460
If you don't have a dog, put
a dog bowl out on the porch.

00:54:32.460 --> 00:54:33.564
It's victim displacement.

00:54:33.564 --> 00:54:35.980
If it's your house or your
neighbor's-- I know this sounds

00:54:35.980 --> 00:54:36.710
horrible.

00:54:36.710 --> 00:54:40.720
I'm not promoting that you
get your neighbors burgled.

00:54:40.720 --> 00:54:43.920
But if you put dog bowl
out, and the burglar,

00:54:43.920 --> 00:54:46.340
I have a choice of
two houses, which

00:54:46.340 --> 00:54:48.880
one am I naturally
going to go towards?

00:54:48.880 --> 00:54:51.790
Burglars are funny individuals
in that they're always

00:54:51.790 --> 00:54:53.680
on the lookout for property.

00:54:53.680 --> 00:54:57.634
They've got this
subconscious process going.

00:54:57.634 --> 00:54:59.050
Interesting stuff
about burglary--

00:54:59.050 --> 00:55:01.160
if you live on a
corner house, you're

00:55:01.160 --> 00:55:04.700
more likely to be burgled than
if you live on the street.

00:55:04.700 --> 00:55:07.660
Remember what I was saying about
promoters, crime promoters,

00:55:07.660 --> 00:55:12.500
exit routes, corner house,
multiple exit routes.

00:55:12.500 --> 00:55:15.440
That's by the by.

00:55:15.440 --> 00:55:17.939
So I understand something
about the burglar's mentality.

00:55:17.939 --> 00:55:19.480
So the burglar, by
and large, doesn't

00:55:19.480 --> 00:55:21.100
want to interact with you.

00:55:21.100 --> 00:55:23.230
They want to steal
the stuff and go.

00:55:23.230 --> 00:55:25.420
So let's say you hear
that bump in the night.

00:55:28.340 --> 00:55:32.865
You want to give that
burglar time to escape.

00:55:32.865 --> 00:55:34.240
Because what you
don't want to do

00:55:34.240 --> 00:55:37.210
is put them on the spot
where they feel hemmed in,

00:55:37.210 --> 00:55:40.400
pressurized, and now it's going
to be some sort of a hostage

00:55:40.400 --> 00:55:42.260
type situation in
your house or they

00:55:42.260 --> 00:55:46.240
feel they need to deal
with you as a threat.

00:55:46.240 --> 00:55:52.570
Maybe if it's downstairs, get
your partner, call the police.

00:55:52.570 --> 00:55:56.000
As they're doing that, stand
at the top of the stairs

00:55:56.000 --> 00:55:58.900
or somewhere and just shout
down, we've called the police,

00:55:58.900 --> 00:56:01.460
they're going to be
here in five minutes.

00:56:01.460 --> 00:56:05.204
Five minutes is enough
time for somebody to go.

00:56:05.204 --> 00:56:06.620
If you say something
like, they're

00:56:06.620 --> 00:56:12.880
going to be here any minute,
or hear the sirens coming up,

00:56:12.880 --> 00:56:15.485
that's when you
might spook them.

00:56:15.485 --> 00:56:17.860
And remember what we were
talking about stress and duress

00:56:17.860 --> 00:56:22.140
and how your decision-making
ability is affected?

00:56:22.140 --> 00:56:24.920
It's the same of the
aggressor and predator.

00:56:24.920 --> 00:56:28.110
They will also be adrenalized,
and their decision making

00:56:28.110 --> 00:56:30.480
process will be affected.

00:56:30.480 --> 00:56:33.920
So again, you've got to
accept the possibility

00:56:33.920 --> 00:56:36.420
that they might
do something rash.

00:56:36.420 --> 00:56:38.260
But by and large,
most burglars don't

00:56:38.260 --> 00:56:39.860
want to interact with you.

00:56:39.860 --> 00:56:43.170
They want to steal your
goods, and they want to go.

00:56:43.170 --> 00:56:46.940
Another thing to be aware
of, if you have been burgled,

00:56:46.940 --> 00:56:49.270
most burglars know that
your insurance takes

00:56:49.270 --> 00:56:52.150
a certain amount
of time to clear

00:56:52.150 --> 00:56:56.050
and that you'll go out and
buy new goods to replace.

00:56:56.050 --> 00:57:01.570
So never go light in terms
of upping your security.

00:57:01.570 --> 00:57:04.170
A lot people will go,
I've been burgled,

00:57:04.170 --> 00:57:06.580
and it's kind of like, I ought
to do something about it.

00:57:06.580 --> 00:57:08.240
I ought to get a
security system.

00:57:08.240 --> 00:57:09.700
I ought to do something.

00:57:09.700 --> 00:57:12.290
And after a week
or so, it doesn't

00:57:12.290 --> 00:57:14.430
seem so immediate a need.

00:57:14.430 --> 00:57:15.780
I'll see to it later.

00:57:15.780 --> 00:57:17.740
Be aware that your house
is kind of-- they've

00:57:17.740 --> 00:57:21.940
broken into it once,
they know how to get in.

00:57:21.940 --> 00:57:23.690
And you really want
to be doing a security

00:57:23.690 --> 00:57:25.530
assessment of your property.

00:57:25.530 --> 00:57:30.250
And that includes basement
doors and garage doors.

00:57:30.250 --> 00:57:32.780
They're probably the two
which get overlooked.

00:57:32.780 --> 00:57:35.430
I've got this sturdy front door.

00:57:35.430 --> 00:57:37.920
But if your basement
door is rotting

00:57:37.920 --> 00:57:42.430
and I can kick the lock down,
I'm now in your basement,

00:57:42.430 --> 00:57:46.220
and there's no natural
surveillance in your basement.

00:57:46.220 --> 00:57:49.510
So I've got all the time in the
world to effectively hack away

00:57:49.510 --> 00:57:52.816
at that interior door
to get into your house.

00:57:52.816 --> 00:57:54.190
And this goes,
again, what you're

00:57:54.190 --> 00:57:55.810
looking for is
natural surveillance.

00:57:55.810 --> 00:58:00.260
So if you've got high fences,
bushes, shrubbery, cut it down

00:58:00.260 --> 00:58:03.440
so people can actually
see in so there's not

00:58:03.440 --> 00:58:06.835
anywhere for somebody to
spend time breaking in.

00:58:06.835 --> 00:58:08.640
So that makes sense.

00:58:08.640 --> 00:58:10.570
Any other questions?

00:58:10.570 --> 00:58:11.160
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:58:11.160 --> 00:58:12.800
So you talked at
length about how

00:58:12.800 --> 00:58:15.040
to be aware and
recognize situations

00:58:15.040 --> 00:58:16.771
when there's a threat coming.

00:58:16.771 --> 00:58:19.020
And you also talked about
what to do when it's already

00:58:19.020 --> 00:58:22.260
the point of the knife
being held against you.

00:58:22.260 --> 00:58:25.380
So what can you do in
the five or ten seconds

00:58:25.380 --> 00:58:27.200
preceding that to avoid it?

00:58:27.200 --> 00:58:27.797
Do you run?

00:58:27.797 --> 00:58:30.130
What do you do if someone is
following right behind you?

00:58:30.130 --> 00:58:30.690
Do you run?

00:58:30.690 --> 00:58:31.564
Do you confront them?

00:58:31.564 --> 00:58:33.034
Do you change course, et cetera?

00:58:33.034 --> 00:58:34.700
GERSHON BEN KEREN:
It's a good question,

00:58:34.700 --> 00:58:36.200
and it's probably
that middle ground

00:58:36.200 --> 00:58:37.790
which confuses most people.

00:58:37.790 --> 00:58:40.320
So you've identified the threat.

00:58:40.320 --> 00:58:42.650
It's not yet to you.

00:58:42.650 --> 00:58:45.135
What can I do in
that interim phase?

00:58:48.550 --> 00:58:50.652
And again, situation
determines the solution,

00:58:50.652 --> 00:58:52.360
so not every one of
these is appropriate.

00:58:55.450 --> 00:58:59.100
Maybe I want to let the person
know that I've identified them,

00:58:59.100 --> 00:59:01.701
that they've lost that
element of surprise.

00:59:01.701 --> 00:59:04.200
And that could be as simple as
making eye contact with them.

00:59:06.770 --> 00:59:08.820
And that's, again,
depending what I believe

00:59:08.820 --> 00:59:11.540
or kind of working
to their motive.

00:59:11.540 --> 00:59:14.190
I probably know that in
a crowded shopping mall,

00:59:14.190 --> 00:59:16.780
somebody is not
trying to abduct me.

00:59:16.780 --> 00:59:20.240
They'll do that more in the
parking lot than in the mall

00:59:20.240 --> 00:59:24.230
itself, so it's more likely
be somebody like a mugger.

00:59:24.230 --> 00:59:27.410
And if they've lost
that element of surprise

00:59:27.410 --> 00:59:30.410
and I can move away,
the chances are

00:59:30.410 --> 00:59:32.990
they're going to just
pick another victim.

00:59:32.990 --> 00:59:37.430
Because I'm making myself
a harder target for them.

00:59:37.430 --> 00:59:39.720
I'm a big fan, where
possible, of getting

00:59:39.720 --> 00:59:42.970
barriers and objects between
me and the person I believe

00:59:42.970 --> 00:59:44.870
who's a potential assailant.

00:59:44.870 --> 00:59:47.340
Parked cars are fantastic.

00:59:47.340 --> 00:59:49.265
Parked cars make a
really good barrier.

00:59:49.265 --> 00:59:50.890
If you're walking on
the street and you

00:59:50.890 --> 00:59:57.070
think somebody's behind
you, move behind it.

00:59:57.070 --> 00:59:59.560
Again, if you interrupt
the plan early enough on,

00:59:59.560 --> 01:00:03.050
they're probably going to pick
somebody else that's a victim.

01:00:03.050 --> 01:00:07.090
And this is why they go
to areas where there's

01:00:07.090 --> 01:00:09.670
a large number of
potential victims.

01:00:09.670 --> 01:00:11.840
And that's why they're
carrying out surveillance--

01:00:11.840 --> 01:00:15.630
to see not only are you
a good potential victim,

01:00:15.630 --> 01:00:17.750
but have you picked up on them.

01:00:17.750 --> 01:00:22.890
So making distance, putting
objects and barriers

01:00:22.890 --> 01:00:27.240
would probably be my short
answer on what to do.

01:00:27.240 --> 01:00:31.470
At a higher level, if I really
think it's going to be violent,

01:00:31.470 --> 01:00:33.652
I'm looking for an
improvised weapon.

01:00:33.652 --> 01:00:36.870
And we talk about this
in the book and the way

01:00:36.870 --> 01:00:40.370
the Israeli Defense
Forces teach people

01:00:40.370 --> 01:00:43.060
how to improvise and
use the environment.

01:00:43.060 --> 01:00:46.510
And it basically involves
categorising objects.

01:00:46.510 --> 01:00:49.572
So I look for objects that
are like a stick, objects that

01:00:49.572 --> 01:00:51.890
are like a knife, et
cetera, et cetera.

01:00:51.890 --> 01:00:54.090
So I can try and make distance.

01:00:54.090 --> 01:00:56.100
I can try and put
objects and barriers.

01:00:56.100 --> 01:00:59.970
That could be simple as a
table if I'm in a restaurant

01:00:59.970 --> 01:01:02.920
or furniture if the assault
is in my house, something

01:01:02.920 --> 01:01:05.710
to slow the person's
advance down

01:01:05.710 --> 01:01:08.700
and that gives me a
chance to either formulate

01:01:08.700 --> 01:01:12.737
another strategy or
basically make my escape,

01:01:12.737 --> 01:01:14.695
and then looking for
objects in the environment

01:01:14.695 --> 01:01:16.750
that I can use to
protect myself with.

01:01:16.750 --> 01:01:19.360
So that, again, would
be my short answer.

01:01:19.360 --> 01:01:22.710
But really, if in
that situation you

01:01:22.710 --> 01:01:26.010
came up with a solution--
somebody is behind me,

01:01:26.010 --> 01:01:28.170
would running work?

01:01:28.170 --> 01:01:28.880
There you go.

01:01:28.880 --> 01:01:30.560
That's your solution.

01:01:30.560 --> 01:01:34.300
You don't really need to
consider any of the others.

01:01:34.300 --> 01:01:36.040
And the problem we
often have is our ego

01:01:36.040 --> 01:01:37.511
gets in the way of
those solutions,

01:01:37.511 --> 01:01:39.510
because we don't want to
look like the guy who's

01:01:39.510 --> 01:01:42.220
running away from somebody.

01:01:42.220 --> 01:01:43.450
But you know what?

01:01:43.450 --> 01:01:47.900
There's only one of me,
and my survival is key.

01:01:47.900 --> 01:01:50.585
And if I look a bit
of an idiot, hey,

01:01:50.585 --> 01:01:52.460
I've lived my life
looking a bit of an idiot.

01:01:52.460 --> 01:01:54.282
I can cope with that.

01:01:54.282 --> 01:01:56.250
Does that make sense?

01:01:56.250 --> 01:01:57.084
Any other questions?

01:01:57.084 --> 01:01:58.458
AUDIENCE: How
would the heuristic

01:01:58.458 --> 01:02:00.390
change if family
members are present?

01:02:00.390 --> 01:02:02.370
That kind of takes away
the running option.

01:02:02.370 --> 01:02:03.020
GERSHON BEN KEREN: Absolutely.

01:02:03.020 --> 01:02:04.395
And again, this
is something when

01:02:04.395 --> 01:02:06.650
we start building
the decision trees.

01:02:06.650 --> 01:02:08.990
You might need several
decision trees,

01:02:08.990 --> 01:02:11.550
and that's why we have the
situational components,

01:02:11.550 --> 01:02:14.600
to start altering
the heuristics.

01:02:14.600 --> 01:02:15.520
Kids are a hard one.

01:02:18.180 --> 01:02:19.860
A lot of it will
depend on how you've

01:02:19.860 --> 01:02:22.290
educated your kid as
to personal safety

01:02:22.290 --> 01:02:26.620
and whether you've included
them in on your plan or not.

01:02:26.620 --> 01:02:28.930
And this can be a frightening
thing for an adult

01:02:28.930 --> 01:02:32.110
to do, to say to a kid, if
we're ever in a situation

01:02:32.110 --> 01:02:34.870
where somebody is aggressive
towards me or your dad,

01:02:34.870 --> 01:02:36.700
this is what we're going to do.

01:02:36.700 --> 01:02:40.240
So you might try and
work out a decision tree

01:02:40.240 --> 01:02:41.960
with your kid in mind,
and a lot of that

01:02:41.960 --> 01:02:45.040
might be based on your
kid's personality.

01:02:45.040 --> 01:02:47.990
And this could be one
where, in terms of fighting,

01:02:47.990 --> 01:02:51.430
you really don't want to be
the guy who's seen by your kid

01:02:51.430 --> 01:02:54.770
beating seven shades of
snot out of somebody.

01:02:54.770 --> 01:02:57.100
That's a consideration as well.

01:02:57.100 --> 01:02:59.200
I think this macho idea
that your kid wants

01:02:59.200 --> 01:03:04.090
to see your dad defend them,
I think that's a nice idea.

01:03:04.090 --> 01:03:06.720
I think when you look at what
the realities of violence are,

01:03:06.720 --> 01:03:09.780
you might not want to present
that image to your kid.

01:03:09.780 --> 01:03:12.840
So it could be that-- say
you're with your partner

01:03:12.840 --> 01:03:17.970
and the kid, that your decision
tree is, first sign of threat,

01:03:17.970 --> 01:03:22.650
child gets behind me,
moves away with mom.

01:03:22.650 --> 01:03:25.010
So you make yourself
the guy on your own.

01:03:25.010 --> 01:03:31.020
So you basically remove
those two third parties

01:03:31.020 --> 01:03:32.840
away from the scene
so that you can

01:03:32.840 --> 01:03:36.120
work through
heuristics on your own.

01:03:36.120 --> 01:03:38.730
It could be in worst
case scenarios--

01:03:38.730 --> 01:03:45.310
and again, this is really to
think about whether it's best--

01:03:45.310 --> 01:03:48.870
to tell your kid, you know what,
this is not a good situation

01:03:48.870 --> 01:03:50.396
for you to be with.

01:03:50.396 --> 01:03:52.020
You need to find
somebody else to alert

01:03:52.020 --> 01:03:54.570
that there's danger going on.

01:03:54.570 --> 01:03:56.400
And one of the things
with educating kids

01:03:56.400 --> 01:03:58.441
is you have to see the
world through a kid's eyes

01:03:58.441 --> 01:03:59.970
when you do this.

01:03:59.970 --> 01:04:06.029
So often, people will say,
go and get a policeman.

01:04:06.029 --> 01:04:07.570
Often, kids don't
know the difference

01:04:07.570 --> 01:04:11.270
between policemen
and security guards.

01:04:11.270 --> 01:04:14.320
They're just basically
in the same uniform.

01:04:14.320 --> 01:04:17.110
And also, under stress and
duress, which a kid will be,

01:04:17.110 --> 01:04:20.810
they'll be seeing the world in a
much more merged and blurry way

01:04:20.810 --> 01:04:22.290
than a distinct way.

01:04:22.290 --> 01:04:25.180
And if we look at
the professions which

01:04:25.180 --> 01:04:27.470
have yielded some of the
worst child sexual predators,

01:04:27.470 --> 01:04:30.010
security guards are one of them.

01:04:30.010 --> 01:04:33.590
So I don't want to be saying
to my kid, go find a policeman.

01:04:33.590 --> 01:04:36.120
By and large, if you have
to develop a strategy

01:04:36.120 --> 01:04:38.190
and you develop your
own heuristics--

01:04:38.190 --> 01:04:42.140
I would say these
are my heuristics--

01:04:42.140 --> 01:04:46.910
tell your kid to go
and find another woman.

01:04:46.910 --> 01:04:51.675
The number of female child
sexual predators is minute.

01:04:54.590 --> 01:04:57.110
Most women have some
maternal instinct

01:04:57.110 --> 01:04:59.890
and are likely to
look after your kid.

01:04:59.890 --> 01:05:01.390
The other things I
would think about

01:05:01.390 --> 01:05:04.902
is actually having information
about your child on them.

01:05:04.902 --> 01:05:07.360
Because they might not be of
an age where they can remember

01:05:07.360 --> 01:05:10.040
phone numbers, the
house where they live,

01:05:10.040 --> 01:05:12.420
and all of those things.

01:05:12.420 --> 01:05:15.750
So again, your heuristics
have to work for you

01:05:15.750 --> 01:05:18.310
according to your
base and skill set.

01:05:18.310 --> 01:05:20.740
And they might involve
telling your kid,

01:05:20.740 --> 01:05:23.180
because of the situation
and your skill set,

01:05:23.180 --> 01:05:26.650
that they need to go and find
somebody to deal with this.

01:05:26.650 --> 01:05:28.970
Because they're a liability
with you and likely to get

01:05:28.970 --> 01:05:34.760
harmed, and they're better
off in another location.

01:05:34.760 --> 01:05:37.590
That's a hard thing to do.

01:05:37.590 --> 01:05:40.500
And again, I would always say
when you talk about safety

01:05:40.500 --> 01:05:43.230
with your kids, they're often
a lot more mature about it

01:05:43.230 --> 01:05:45.690
than we think.

01:05:45.690 --> 01:05:47.560
They often have a
better understanding

01:05:47.560 --> 01:05:52.580
and are a lot more receptive
and a lot more sensible

01:05:52.580 --> 01:05:54.450
surrounding solutions.

01:05:54.450 --> 01:05:56.659
We as parents--
I'm a parent-- tend

01:05:56.659 --> 01:05:58.700
to think they're going to
get freaked out as soon

01:05:58.700 --> 01:06:01.070
as we start talking
about violence.

01:06:01.070 --> 01:06:03.270
That hasn't been my experience.

01:06:03.270 --> 01:06:06.960
But I think you have to do it
in a mature, non-sensational

01:06:06.960 --> 01:06:11.030
fashion and present it more
with, if somebody starts

01:06:11.030 --> 01:06:14.490
to behave aggressively towards
me and I tell you to do this,

01:06:14.490 --> 01:06:17.222
this is what you do.

01:06:17.222 --> 01:06:18.680
And it could be as
simple as things

01:06:18.680 --> 01:06:20.880
like putting your
kid in the car.

01:06:20.880 --> 01:06:22.430
The other thing
to always consider

01:06:22.430 --> 01:06:25.080
is it's the same as the thing
about when you're in a plane--

01:06:25.080 --> 01:06:28.090
put your own oxygen
mask on first.

01:06:28.090 --> 01:06:30.851
If you're not able to
keep yourself safe,

01:06:30.851 --> 01:06:32.392
then there's not a
guarantee that you

01:06:32.392 --> 01:06:34.900
can keep your kids safe.

01:06:34.900 --> 01:06:36.970
And that's always a
big concern as well--

01:06:36.970 --> 01:06:39.570
are you doing something in this
situation which is actually

01:06:39.570 --> 01:06:43.300
going to put you in more harm?

01:06:43.300 --> 01:06:45.780
To be honest, I would work
off the same simple heuristic.

01:06:45.780 --> 01:06:47.290
If somebody wants
money, et cetera,

01:06:47.290 --> 01:06:50.680
et cetera, off me, there you go.

01:06:50.680 --> 01:06:54.690
If you want me, if you want my
kid, if you want me and my kid,

01:06:54.690 --> 01:06:56.280
you know what?

01:06:56.280 --> 01:06:59.260
Sorry, I'm going to have to deal
with you physically for that.

01:06:59.260 --> 01:07:02.220
If it's a case of
bullying and intimidation,

01:07:02.220 --> 01:07:06.380
I think it's a much better
way of basically sucking it

01:07:06.380 --> 01:07:10.440
up, putting your ego in
check, letting it happen.

01:07:10.440 --> 01:07:15.226
We fight for two
reasons-- ego or survival.

01:07:15.226 --> 01:07:18.840
It's a famous quote
from Dr. Gabriel Snyder.

01:07:18.840 --> 01:07:20.430
They're the two
reasons you basically

01:07:20.430 --> 01:07:22.580
fight-- ego or survival.

01:07:22.580 --> 01:07:24.430
So if the situation
you're facing

01:07:24.430 --> 01:07:30.350
is one where it's a matter of
ego, be the bigger man on that.

01:07:30.350 --> 01:07:33.760
One of the things I always do
when I'm confronting violence

01:07:33.760 --> 01:07:40.210
is I decide whether a
situation is premeditated--

01:07:40.210 --> 01:07:44.650
that is, somebody has come
to that situation basically

01:07:44.650 --> 01:07:47.790
wanting to harm me--
or if it's spontaneous.

01:07:47.790 --> 01:07:50.610
Has something I've done
or perceived to have done

01:07:50.610 --> 01:07:52.840
caused the person to become
aggressive-- so spill

01:07:52.840 --> 01:07:56.140
a drink over them, cut them
off in a parking space.

01:07:56.140 --> 01:07:57.680
And in those
situations, I can use

01:07:57.680 --> 01:07:59.950
a lot of deescalation skills.

01:07:59.950 --> 01:08:02.290
So when I build my really,
really top level decision

01:08:02.290 --> 01:08:06.820
tree, is it premeditated,
is it spontaneous?

01:08:06.820 --> 01:08:09.650
If it's premeditated,
do they want me?

01:08:09.650 --> 01:08:12.000
Do they want my things?

01:08:12.000 --> 01:08:14.070
And then I go into
that decision tree.

01:08:14.070 --> 01:08:17.420
If it's spontaneous, I
assess their emotional state.

01:08:17.420 --> 01:08:18.510
Can I deescalate?

01:08:18.510 --> 01:08:20.270
Can I disengage?

01:08:20.270 --> 01:08:23.170
So again, we can build the
decision tree a little higher.

01:08:23.170 --> 01:08:26.129
With third parties involved,
I would include them

01:08:26.129 --> 01:08:26.920
in your heuristics.

01:08:26.920 --> 01:08:28.578
Does that makes sense?

01:08:28.578 --> 01:08:29.534
Anything else?

01:08:32.880 --> 01:08:33.630
OK, guys.

01:08:33.630 --> 01:08:36.210
Thank you very, very
much for listening.

01:08:36.210 --> 01:08:39.740
I hope you never have to use
the physical skills in the book

01:08:39.740 --> 01:08:42.590
and that the personal safety
skills of threat recognition

01:08:42.590 --> 01:08:44.279
and the decision-making
skills are

01:08:44.279 --> 01:08:47.680
what allows you to identify,
avoid, and protect violence.

01:08:47.680 --> 01:08:48.820
Thank you very much.

01:08:48.820 --> 01:08:51.838
[APPLAUSE]

